s=\"inline\">call, find, consider, see, view<\/ul><span class=\"p\">These words all mean to think about somebody\/something in a particular way.<\/span><ul class=\"deflist\"><li class=\"li\"><span class=\"dt\">regard<\/span> <span class=\"dd\">to think of somebody\/something in a particular way: <span class=\"unx\">He seemed to regard the whole thing as a joke.<\/span><\/span><\/li><li class=\"li\"><span class=\"dt\">call<\/span> <span class=\"dd\">to say that somebody\/something has particular qualities or characteristics: <span class=\"unx\">I wouldn\u2019t call German an easy language.<\/span><\/span><\/li><li class=\"li\"><span class=\"dt\">find<\/span> <span class=\"dd\">to have a particular feeling or opinion about something: <span class=\"unx\">You may find your illness hard to accept.<\/span><\/span><\/li><li class=\"li\"><span class=\"dt\">consider<\/span> <span class=\"dd\">to think of somebody\/something in a particular way: <span class=\"unx\">Who do you consider (to be) responsible for the accident?<\/span><\/span><\/li><\/ul> <div class=\"un\"><span class=\"h4\">regard or consider?<\/span><span class=\"p\">These two words have the same meaning, but they are used in different patterns and structures. In this meaning <span class=\"eb\">consider<\/span> must be used with a complement or clause: you can <span class=\"ei\">consider somebody\/something to be something<\/span> or <span class=\"ei\">consider somebody\/something as something<\/span>, although very often the <span class=\"ei\">to be<\/span> or <span class=\"ei\">as<\/span> is left out: <span class=\"ei\">He considers himself an expert.<\/span><span class=\"ei\">They are considered a high-risk group.<\/span> You can also <span class=\"ei\">consider that somebody\/something is something<\/span> and again, the <span class=\"ei\">that<\/span> can be left out. <span class=\"eb\">Regard<\/span> is used in a narrower range of structures. The most frequent structure is <span class=\"ei\">regard somebody\/something as something<\/span>; the <span class=\"ei\">as<\/span> cannot be left out: <span class=\"wx\">I regard him a close friend.<\/span> You cannot <span class=\"wx\">regard somebody\/something to be something<\/span> or <span class=\"wx\">regard that somebody\/something is something.<\/span> However, <span class=\"eb\">regard<\/span> (but not <span class=\"eb\">consider<\/span> in this meaning) can also be used without a noun or adjective complement but with just an object and adverb <span class=\"ei\">(somebody\/something is highly regarded)<\/span> or adverbial phrase (<span class=\"ei\">regard somebody\/something with suspicion\/jealousy\/admiration)<\/span>.<\/span><\/div><ul class=\"deflist\"><li class=\"li\"><span class=\"dt\">see<\/span> <span class=\"dd\">to have an opinion of something: <span class=\"unx\">Try to see things from her point of view.<\/span><\/span><\/li><li class=\"li\"><span class=\"dt\">view<\/span> <span class=\"dd\">to think of somebody\/something in a particular way: <span class=\"unx\">How do you view your position within the company?<\/span> <div class=\"un\"><span class=\"eb\">View<\/span> has the same meaning as <span class=\"eb\">regard<\/span> and <span class=\"eb\">consider<\/span> but is slightly less frequent and slightly less formal. The main structures are <span class=\"ei\">view somebody\/something as somebody\/something<\/span> (you cannot leave out the <span class=\"ei\">as<\/span>) and <span class=\"ei\">view somebody\/something with something<\/span>.<\/div><\/span><\/li><\/ul><span class=\"patterns\">Patterns<\/span><ul class=\"bullet\"><li class=\"li\">to regard\/consider\/see\/view somebody\/something <span class=\"eb\">as<\/span> something <\/li><li class=\"li\">to regard\/consider\/see\/view somebody\/something <span class=\"eb\">from<\/span> a particular point of view<\/li><li class=\"li\">to find\/consider somebody\/something <span class=\"eb\">to be<\/span> something<\/li><li class=\"li\"><span class=\"eb\